{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:35:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:35:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16009"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16009"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8700"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114800"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8700"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96803"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20817"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114800"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, the face forms from several prominences that grow and fuse together. The development of nasal structures begins in week 4 of development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures directly gives rise to the external nostrils during facial development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nasal placode","Nasal pit","Stomodeum","Intermaxillary segment","Medial nasal prominence"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring facial development, the \u003Cstrong\u003Enasal placode\u003C/strong\u003E appears first as a thickened region of surface ectoderm. This placode invaginates to form the \u003Cstrong\u003Enasal pit\u003C/strong\u003E, which directly develops into the external nostrils. The \u003Cstrong\u003Estomodeum\u003C/strong\u003E is the primitive mouth cavity, while the \u003Cstrong\u003Eintermaxillary segment\u003C/strong\u003E forms from the fusion of medial nasal prominences and gives rise to the philtrum of the upper lip. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial nasal prominence\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to the bridge of the nose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe developmental sequence involves the nasal placode forming in the frontonasal prominence, then invaginating to form the nasal pit. The nasal pit deepens to form nostrils while surrounding mesenchyme forms the nasal prominences.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The nasal pit forms by invagination of the nasal placode during week 4 of embryonic development","The nasal pit directly develops into the nostrils during facial formation","The nasal prominences form from mesenchyme surrounding the nasal pit"],"references":["Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Som PM, Naidich TP. Illustrated review of the embryology and development of the facial region, part 1: Early face and lateral nasal cavities. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2013 Dec;34(12):2233-40. doi: 10.3174/ajnr.A3415. Epub 2013 Mar 14. PMID: 23493891; PMCID: PMC7965203"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96803"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16009"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/i